(241,1,'2013-05-19 04:52:56','2013-05-19 04:52:56','I recently decided to do a bit of finals procrastination by working on a problem that\'s been a mild nuisance for the past few months. My Google Contacts have had a problem with delineating first and last names, but that\'s a story for another post. If you\'re interested in the repo as it develops, check out https://github.com/andrewychoi/fix_contacts\n\nWhat I had been having trouble with was the consistent need to enter a username and password for every time that I wanted to <code>git push</code> to the server. I went into the GitHub user menu and added an SSH key, but access to my accounts was still problematic.\n\nThe problem was that my <code>project_directory/.git/config</code> file still told me that <code>origin</code> was to be reached over HTTPS. Changing that to SSH solved the protocol access problem. For exactness, I changed the line\n\n<code>https://github.com/username/project.git</code>\n\nto\n\n<code>ssh://github.com/username/project.git</code>\n\nNow, however, I was greeted with a\n\n<code>Permission denied (publickey).\nfatal: The remote end hung up unexpectedly</code>\n\nAt this point, I started searching the web for the solution to this problem. It turns out that I needed to SSH in as the <code>git</code> user. The fix was to change\n\n<code>ssh://github.com/username/project.git</code>\n\nto\n\n<code>ssh://git@github.com/username/project.git</code>\n\nNow everything works like a charm!\n\n<code>\n&gt; git pull\nAlready up-to-date.\n&gt; git push\nEverything up-to-date.\n</code>','Ensuring GitHub access over SSH','','inherit','open','open','','95-revision','','','2013-05-19 04:52:56','2013-05-19 04:52:56','',95,'http://www.andrewychoi.com/2013/95-revision/',0,'revision','',0),
(251,1,'2013-07-03 03:47:32','2013-07-03 03:47:32','I\'m learning the lesson that I need to write these posts right after I run the installations; I\'m having trouble reconstructing what I did that got my machine to the point it is now (I tried replicating some of these steps on a clean 12.04 install, and for whatever reason I still can\'t get <code>virtualenv</code> to work correctly).\n\nIn any case, I decided to take a more proactive approach in moving the wide array of Python libraries to Python 3, and start building my personal projects using Py3k. I\'ll be posting periodically about new libraries that I\'ve helped port over; I expect that the majority of them will be \n\nIn no particular order: steps that I took to get a <code>virtualenv</code> with Python 3.3 working on Ubuntu 12.04:\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Install Felix Krull\'s PPA for Python versions: <code>sudo add-apt-repository ppa:fkrull/deadsnakes</code></li>\n	<li>Install Python 3.3: <code>sudo aptitude install python3.3</code></li>\n	<li>Install <code>pip</code> for Python 3.3: <code>sudo aptitude install python3-setuptools</code></li>\n	<li>Create the <code>virtualenv</code>: <code>virtualenv -p /usr/bin/python3.3 target_directory</code></li>\n</ul>\n\nIf I come up with something else that I did to solve this problem, I\'ll be sure to update!','Python 3.3 with virtualenv and Ubuntu 12.04','','inherit','open','open','','108-revision-2','','','2013-07-03 03:47:32','2013-07-03 03:47:32','',108,'http://www.andrewychoi.com/2013/108-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),
(261,1,'2013-07-03 00:17:40','2013-07-03 04:17:40','I got the hankering to try converting this blog to a static site (a la Jekyll, which my Ruby friends keep bringing up) and did some searching for Python equivalents. Putting aside Hyde (which I actually found by just searching \"hyde static site generator\" on a whim, without realizing that the Hyde project actually existed) the best thing for me seemed to be Pelican, which has a great migration tool (<code>pelican-import</code>) for migrating from Wordpress.\r\n\r\nIn terms of getting set up, there were a bunch of dependencies that needed to be satisfied; here are just a few of the ones that seemed to trip me up (the rest of them are a simple <code>pip install beautifulsoup4</code> or similar).\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><code>pandoc</code> is a bit tricky, you need to install it via <code>sudo aptitude install pandoc</code> as opposed to a <code>pip</code> package.</li>\r\n	<li>Trying to run the importer: <code>pelican-import --wpfiles wp.file.xml</code> failed with:\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n...\r\nbs4.FeatureNotFound: Couldn\'t find a tree builder with the features you requested: xml. Do you need to install a parser library?</blockquote>\r\n\r\nwhich prompted an attempt to install <code>lxml</code>, via <code>pip install lxml</code>, which then failed with\r\n\r\n<blockquote>...\r\n/home/andrew/workspace/personal-site/build/lxml/src/lxml/includes/etree_defs.h:9:31: fatal error: libxml/xmlversion.h: No such file or directory</blockquote>\r\n\r\nwhich I did some Googling to find that the solution was to run <code>sudo aptitude install libxml2-dev libxslt-dev</code> after which rerunning <code>pip install lxml</code> was enough to get the importer working!</li>\r\n</ul>','Pelican on Ubuntu 12.04 and Python 3.3','','publish','open','open','','pelican-on-ubuntu-12-04-and-python-3-3','','','2013-07-03 00:17:40','2013-07-03 04:17:40','',0,'http://www.andrewychoi.com/?p=261',0,'post','',0),
