(421,1,'2014-06-12 17:34:15','2014-06-12 21:34:15','If you\'re using <code>mchung</code>\'s Heroku buildpack for WordPress (located at <a title=\"https://github.com/mchung/heroku-buildpack-wordpress\" href=\"https://github.com/mchung/heroku-buildpack-wordpress\">https://github.com/mchung/heroku-buildpack-wordpress</a>), like I am, it may be non-obvious how to update your WordPress install. There are two main steps that you need to take.\r\n\r\nFirst, in the Heroku dashboard, under Settings, click on \"Show config vars\", and then \"Edit\". Change <code>WORDPRESS_VERSION</code> to the latest (as of right now, 3.9.1), and then click save.\r\n\r\nThen, to trigger a rebuild, push an empty commit to your repository like so:\r\n<pre>git commit --allow-empty -m \"empty commit\"\r\ngit push heroku master</pre>\r\nThen, when prompted, update your database, and you\'re done!','Updating the Wordpress version on Heroku','','publish','open','open','','updating-the-wordpress-version-on-heroku','','','2014-06-12 17:34:16','2014-06-12 21:34:16','',0,'http://www.andrewychoi.com/?p=421',0,'post','',0),
(431,1,'2014-06-12 17:34:16','2014-06-12 21:34:16','If you\'re using <code>mchung</code>\'s Heroku buildpack for WordPress (located at <a title=\"https://github.com/mchung/heroku-buildpack-wordpress\" href=\"https://github.com/mchung/heroku-buildpack-wordpress\">https://github.com/mchung/heroku-buildpack-wordpress</a>), like I am, it may be non-obvious how to update your WordPress install. There are two main steps that you need to take.\r\n\r\nFirst, in the Heroku dashboard, under Settings, click on \"Show config vars\", and then \"Edit\". Change <code>WORDPRESS_VERSION</code> to the latest (as of right now, 3.9.1), and then click save.\r\n\r\nThen, to trigger a rebuild, push an empty commit to your repository like so:\r\n<pre>git commit --allow-empty -m \"empty commit\"\r\ngit push heroku master</pre>\r\nThen, when prompted, update your database, and you\'re done!','Updating the Wordpress version on Heroku','','inherit','open','open','','421-revision-v1','','','2014-06-12 17:34:16','2014-06-12 21:34:16','',421,'http://www.andrewychoi.com/2014/421-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
(441,1,'2014-06-12 17:47:28','2014-06-12 21:47:28','I\'m currently on a Verizon FiOS connection here at home, and I found that when entering one word terms into my URL bar in Firefox, I would get redirected to <code>search.dnsassist.verizon.com</code> for search results. Interestingly, this did not happen when I entered terms separated by spaces. My intuition led me to believe that this was a DNS resolution service, that was somehow not getting triggered by things that Firefox didn\'t believe were valid URLs. To fix these results, I changed my IPv4 settings on my (now 14.04 LTS, thank goodness) Ubuntu install to use DHCP only for local addressing. I changed my DNS records to point at Google\'s public facing DNS servers, at <code>8.8.8.8</code> and <code>8.8.4.4</code>. Now, since my computer is no longer looking on the local network for a DNS server (and thus not getting results from Verizon\'s servers) I can enter a single term and get my Google search!\r\n\r\nA note: those public-facing DNS server IP addresses are good to memorize, in case you get into a situation where you\'re missing a DNS server. This actually happened to me one time in 2010, when I was working as an IT technician at a hotel conference. The IPv6 addresses are a bit harder to memorize, but they can all be found <a href=\"https://developers.google.com/speed/public-dns/docs/using\">here on Google\'s site</a>.','Removing Verizon DNS Search Assist','','publish','open','open','','removing-verizon-dns-search-assist','','','2014-06-12 17:47:28','2014-06-12 21:47:28','',0,'http://www.andrewychoi.com/?p=441',0,'post','',3),
