(581,1,'2014-08-14 21:25:39','2014-08-15 01:25:39','A quick gotcha that I found today:\r\n\r\nWhile you can compare <code>int</code> values with other <code>int</code> values and it works as expected, the same is not true of many other types. I was aware of the fact that you should use <code>!=</code> for string comparison (because when you use <code>is</code>, Python checks to see if the address of the underlying string is the same), but I just found out that you have to use <code>!=</code> for comparison of floats. It seems that unlike <code>int</code> values, where Python has a single object per value, <code>float</code> values are different!','a is not b vs a != b for float comparison in Python','','publish','open','open','','a-is-not-b-vs-a-b-for-float-comparison-in-python','','','2014-08-14 21:25:39','2014-08-15 01:25:39','',0,'http://www.andrewychoi.com/?p=581',0,'post','',0),
