(601,1,'2014-08-19 15:27:40','2014-08-19 19:27:40','Today I needed to set up a local copy of the Postgres database that we have on a Heroku instance somewhere in the cloud for testing and debugging purposes on my local machine. Steps taken:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Create a new Postgres user:\r\n<pre>&gt; psql -d postgres # default user that postgres creates when you install it\r\npostgres=# create user your_username;\r\n</pre>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Create a database for your app:\r\n<pre>postgres=# create database your_db_name;\r\n</pre>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Grant the user permissions to create databases (this is necessary for running Django tests):\r\n<pre>postgres=# alter user your_username createdb;\r\n</pre>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nDump the data from your Heroku backup (you did download that already, right?)\r\n<pre>\r\npg_restore --verbose --clean --no-acl --no-owner -h localhost -U your_username -d your_dbname /path/to/your/backup.dump \r\n</pre>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\nAnd now you should have a local copy of your DB, as well as the ability to run tests!','Setting up a local Postgres environment','','publish','open','open','','setting-up-a-local-postgres-environment','','','2014-08-19 15:27:40','2014-08-19 19:27:40','',0,'http://www.andrewychoi.com/?p=601',0,'post','',0),
(611,1,'2014-08-19 15:27:40','2014-08-19 19:27:40','Today I needed to set up a local copy of the Postgres database that we have on a Heroku instance somewhere in the cloud for testing and debugging purposes on my local machine. Steps taken:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Create a new Postgres user:\r\n<pre>&gt; psql -d postgres # default user that postgres creates when you install it\r\npostgres=# create user your_username;\r\n</pre>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Create a database for your app:\r\n<pre>postgres=# create database your_db_name;\r\n</pre>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Grant the user permissions to create databases (this is necessary for running Django tests):\r\n<pre>postgres=# alter user your_username createdb;\r\n</pre>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nDump the data from your Heroku backup (you did download that already, right?)\r\n<pre>\r\npg_restore --verbose --clean --no-acl --no-owner -h localhost -U your_username -d your_dbname /path/to/your/backup.dump \r\n</pre>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\nAnd now you should have a local copy of your DB, as well as the ability to run tests!','Setting up a local Postgres environment','','inherit','open','open','','601-revision-v1','','','2014-08-19 15:27:40','2014-08-19 19:27:40','',601,'http://www.andrewychoi.com/2014/601-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
(621,1,'2014-08-25 12:37:48','2014-08-25 16:37:48','I\'m building a tool to export results from a Django ORM query to JSON, and today I ran into a bug that would have taken a whole lot longer to debug had I not known about iterators and how they work. (For a primer, check out https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/classes.html#iterators or something similar). My code had a section in it where I use the groupby() function in the itertools package to group results so that I can represent them hierarchically. So, my code looked a bit like this:\r\n<pre>\r\nsave_dict = {}\r\nfor key, group in itertools.groupby(thing_to_group, key = lambda x: x[\"group_key\"]):\r\nprint key\r\nfor item in group:\r\nprint item\r\nsave_dict[key] = {item[\"subkey\"]: item[\"value\"] for item in group}\r\n</pre>\r\nBut when I printed out my results, I found:\r\n<pre>\r\n> save_dict[key]\r\n{}\r\n</pre>\r\nThe dictionary was empty!\r\n\r\nThe issue with my code was that by going through the group iterator already, I had \"exhausted\" the iterator, and so the dict comprehension was operating on an empty iterable. Removing the offending value checking code solved the problem!\r\n\r\nFor future reference, if you need to retain the values from the iterable, use the handy list() function (taken from: https://docs.python.org/2/library/itertools.html#itertools.groupby) like so:\r\n<pre>\r\nfor key, group in itertools.groupby(thing_to_group, key = lambda x: x[\"group_key\"]):\r\nsaved_group = list(group)\r\nfor item in saved_group:\r\nprint item # you get to eat all your values\r\nfor item in saved_group:\r\nprint item # and have them too!\r\nsave_dict[key] = {item[\"subkey\"]: item[\"value\"] for item in group} # this will work now\r\n</pre>','Iterators: not even twice','','publish','open','open','','iterators-not-even-twice','','','2014-08-25 12:37:48','2014-08-25 16:37:48','',0,'http://www.andrewychoi.com/?p=621',0,'post','',0),
